canonical:
  title: 賀建都北京龍馬出現松柏凝脂表
  author: 卞季良
  language: lzh
  text: 一人御極聿建神都二儀生祥載彰聖德照臨所曁蹈舞惟同竊觀歷代之守成率置兩京而爲治盖因草昧之未暇乃於繼述而有終欽惟勇智邁湯聦明齊舜奉天心而紹先志受此丕基視民利而貽孫謀作新大邑豈惟山川之雄勝且爲道里之適均故令臣庶以擧欣而得禎符之屢見淸水龍文之遍體旣産奇祥孝陵松樹之凝脂復昭上瑞是致多方之趨賀實基萬世之太平慶衍宗祊事光簡策伏念猥將庸質幸際昌辰迹滯靑丘雖阻駿奔之列心馳紫闥倍殫虎拜之誠
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 賀建都北京龍馬出現松柏凝脂表
  author: 卞季良
  language: lzh
  text: 一人御極。聿建神都。二儀生祥。載彰聖德。照臨所曁。蹈舞惟同。竊觀歷代之守成。率置兩京而爲治。盖因草昧之未暇。乃於繼述而有終。欽惟勇智邁湯。聦明齊舜。奉天心而紹先志。受此丕基。視民利而貽孫謀。作新大邑。豈惟山川之雄勝。且爲道里之適均。故令臣庶以擧欣。而得禎符之屢見。淸水龍文之遍體。旣産奇祥。孝陵松樹之凝脂。復昭上瑞。是致多方之趨賀。實基萬世之太平。慶衍宗祊。事光簡策。伏念猥將庸質。幸際昌辰。迹滯靑丘。雖阻駿奔之列。心馳紫闥。倍殫虎拜之誠。
korean:
  title: 북경 건도와 용마의 출현과 송백의 응지를 하례하는 표
  author: 변계량
  language: kor
  text: 한 분이 제위(帝位)에 오르시어 비로소 신도(新都)를 세우시고, 양의(兩儀)가 상서를 낳아 이로써 성덕(聖德)을 나타내니, 해와 달이 비치는 곳은 한결같이 기뻐 춤추나이다. 조용히 보옵건대, 역대(歷代)의 수성(守成)이 모두 양경(兩京)을 두어 다스렸사오니, 대개 초창(草創) 때에는 틈이 없었다가 계술(繼述)할 때에야 유종(有終)하였나이다. 공경히 생각하옵건대, 용지(勇智)는 탕(湯) 임금보다 더하시고 총명은 순(舜) 임금과 같으시와, 하늘의 마음을 받들고 선조(先祖)의 뜻을 이어 이 큰 터를 받으셨고, 백성의 이(利)를 보고 자손을 위한 꾀를 주어 새 큰 도읍을 만드시니, 어찌 다만 산천(山川)의 웅장한 승사로 여길 뿐이오리이까. 또한 도리(道里)도 알맞고 고르나이다. 그러므로 신민(臣民)들이 모두 기뻐하고 상서가 여기저기서 나타나오니, 청수현(淸水縣)에서 나온 용문(龍文)의 말은 이미 진기한 상서를 낳았사온데, 효릉(孝陵) 소나무의 엉긴 송진이 다시 지극한 서징(瑞徵)을 밝히 나타냄으로써 다방(多方)의 추하(趨賀)를 받으시니 실로 만세(萬世)의 태평을 이룩하여, 경사가 종사(宗社)에 넘치고 일이 역사책에 빛내나이다. 엎드려 생각하옵건대, 외람되게 용렬한 자질(資質)로 다행히 성대(盛代)를 만나, 몸이 청구(靑丘)에 제한되어 준분(駿奔)의 열(列)에 참가하지 못하오나, 마음은 자궐(紫闕)로 달려 곱절로 호배(虎拜 제후가 천자에게 조회함)의 정성을 다하옵나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0350_010_0620&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial Presenting Congratulations on the Establishment of the Capital at Beijing and the Auspicious Appearance of the Dragon-Horse and the Resinous Pine at the Imperial Mausoleum
  author: Byeon Gyeyangno
  language: eng
  text: "One sovereign ascends the throne and founds a divine capital. Heaven and earth produce auspicious signs, manifesting the sage's virtue. Wherever the sun and moon illuminate, all hearts dance in unison with joy.\n\nHumble though my observation be, I note that throughout the ages, those who preserved and perfected the realm established two capitals to govern their lands. In the unsettled origins, there was no leisure for such works; only in the succession of later rulers did this design reach completion. I reverently consider: Your Majesty's courage and wisdom surpass even the great Tang, and your sagacity rivals the wise Shun. Receiving Heaven's mandate and continuing the intentions of your ancestors, you accepted this grand foundation. Regarding the welfare of your people and devising plans for your descendants, you have established a great new capital—not merely for the majesty of its mountains and rivers, but also for the fitness and balance of its roads and distances. Thus all your subjects rejoice, and auspicious omens appear from every quarter.\n\nThe dragon-steed that emerged from Clear Water has already brought forth wondrous portents; the resinous pine at the Imperial Mausoleum now shines forth supreme auspices. Through these signs, congratulations flow from all directions, and thereby the peace of ten thousand generations is secured. Blessings overflow upon the ancestral shrine, and these deeds shall illuminate the pages of history. \n\nI humbly reflect that with my humble talents I have been fortunate to encounter this glorious age. Though my body remains bound to this Eastern Land and I cannot join the ranks of those hastening to present themselves before the throne, my heart flies toward the Purple Palace, doubly earnest in the sincerity of my obeisance."
  footnotes:
    - The 'dragon-horse' (용마/龍馬) was considered a celestial auspice in Chinese cosmology, appearing as a sign of dynastic blessing.
    - The 'resinous pine' (송백의 응지/松柏凝脂) at the Imperial Mausoleum (孝陵) signifies the enduring virtue of the imperial lineage.
    - Tang and Shun are ancient sage-kings of legend, representing the highest standards of virtue and wisdom.
    - '''Eastern Land'' (청구/靑丘) is a poetic reference to Korea.'
    - The 'Purple Palace' (자궐/紫闕) refers to the imperial palace at Beijing.
